<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANC URGED TO KEEP SLOVO OUT OF TALKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, South Africa 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Frederik W. de Klerk asked black leader Nelson Mandela to drop 
Communist leader Joe Slovo from his team for talks with Pretoria after the 
state accused Communists in the African National Congress of plotting violence, 
the ANC said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The ANC also said De Klerk and Mandela, the ANC's deputy president, will meet 
again Aug. 1 after indecisive talks Thursday on the mass arrests of Communists 
in the ANC. 
</P>
<P>
They were accused of stockpiling arms in the event power-sharing talks with the 
white minority government fail. 
</P>
<P>
De Klerk "expressed preference for the exclusion" of Slovo, leader of the South 
African Communist Party, from the ANC team due to meet a Cabinet delegation for 
a second round of talks Aug. 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
