<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOUSE ERASES RULE CALLING FOR JULY 31 ADJOURNMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The House moved Friday to wipe an anachronism off its rule book, kicking out a 
provision requiring Congress to adjourn by July 31 every year unless the nation 
is at war. The rule, which has been ignored for years, also faces a Senate 
vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
