<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEXUALITY AND ERASURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Regarding Leslie Carr's July 7 letter about Mike Boehm's review of Erasure's 
concert: I also attended that concert, and while I agree that Erasure put on a 
good show, I disagree completely that singer Andy Bell's homosexuality wasn't 
an issue. 
</P>
<P>
Having seen Erasure when they opened for Duran Duran in 1987, I was aware of 
Bell's flamboyant stage antics, but I considered his sexuality secondary to his 
dynamic performance. 
</P>
<P>
However, I was somewhat unprepared for the audience that Erasure drew as a 
headline act. In my opinion, their show was not a case of a straight audience 
lowering their guard to enjoy a gay performer; it was more like a gay pride 
festival. The rows around me were filled with homosexual couples openly 
displaying affection, and the fact that in the setting of Erasure's concert, 
they felt free to do so seems to me a reflection of Bell's openness about his 
homosexuality. 
</P>
<P>
The reason that the audience wasn't making derogatory remarks about Bell's 
sexuality is that a great deal of the audience was itself homosexual -- not 
because they were straight people "overlooking" the band's sexuality as Carr 
suggested in her letter. 
</P>
<P>
Yes, Erasure did put on an excellent show -- but their homosexuality was a 
prominent aspect of their concert, and it wouldn't have made sense for the 
review to pretend otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
MELISSA HENRY 
</P>
<P>
Garden Grove 
</P>
</TEXT>
